# Uterus

> The uterus is a **hollow, thick-walled, pear-shaped muscular organ** (~7.5 × 5 × 2.5 cm; ~60 g) lying in the lesser pelvis between the bladder and [[Rectum and Anal Canal]]. It is the site of **implantation**, **menstruation**, **gestation**, and **parturition**.

## 🔗 Key Connections
- [[Reproductive System]]
- Superolateral: [[Uterine Tubes]] at uterine horns
- Inferior: [[Cervix]] (internal os → external os)
- Below: [[Vagina]]
- Anterior: Vesico-uterine pouch / bladder
- Posterior: Recto-uterine pouch (Pouch of Douglas) / [[Rectum and Anal Canal]]
- Supported by: [[Broad Ligament]], cardinal (transverse cervical) ligament, uterosacral ligaments, round ligament of uterus
- Blood supply: **Uterine artery** (from internal iliac) — crosses **ureter** at the lateral fornix of vagina ("water under bridge")
- Venous drainage: Uterine venous plexus → internal iliac veins
- Lymphatics: Para-aortic nodes (fundus); internal iliac / obturator nodes (body/cervix)
- Innervation: Uterine plexus; pain from fundus via T10–L1; cervix via S2–S4
- Embryological origin: Müllerian (paramesonephric) duct fusion

## 🔬 Structure

### Parts
| Part | Description |
|------|-------------|
| **Fundus** | Dome above uterine tubes; palpable in pregnancy |
| **Body (corpus)** | Main portion; site of implantation |
| **Isthmus** | Junction of body and cervix; "lower uterine segment" in obstetrics |
| **Cervix** | See [[Cervix]] |

### Layers
| Layer | Description |
|-------|-------------|
| **Perimetrium** | Outer serous layer (peritoneum) |
| **Myometrium** | Thick smooth muscle; 3 layers; generates uterine contractions in labour |
| **Endometrium** | Inner mucosa; functional layer shed in menstruation; basal layer remains |

### Normal Position
- **Anteverted** (long axis of uterus angled forward relative to vagina) and **anteflexed** (body angled forward on cervix) — normal position in ~80%

## ⚙️ Function
- **Menstrual cycle** — endometrium proliferates (oestrogen) and secretes (progesterone); shed if no implantation
- **Implantation** — blastocyst implants in posterior wall of body (day 6–10)
- **Gestation** — myometrium expands to accommodate fetus; placenta formed by trophoblast + decidua
- **Labour** — coordinated myometrial contractions driven by oxytocin + prostaglandins

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Fibroids (leiomyomas)** — most common benign uterine tumour; oestrogen-sensitive; submucosal (menorrhagia), intramural, subserosal
- **Endometriosis** — ectopic endometrial tissue; cyclical pain, dysmenorrhoea, infertility
- **Adenomyosis** — endometrium invades myometrium; bulky uterus, heavy periods
- **Endometrial cancer** — most common gynaecological cancer; post-menopausal bleeding; Type I (oestrogen-related); curettage for diagnosis
- **Uterine rupture** — obstetric emergency; prior caesarean scar predisposes
- **Retroverted uterus** — in ~20%; usually normal variant; can cause dyspareunia

